# Next.js & React Patterns

## Server Components are the default

- Only add `"use client"` when the file uses hooks (`useState`, `useEffect`, `useRef`),
  browser APIs, or event handlers.
- Page components under `app/` are server components by default.
- In Next.js 15, `params` and `searchParams` are Promises:

```typescript
export default async function Page({
  params,
}: {
  params: Promise<{ slug: string }>;
}) {
  const { slug } = await params;
}
```

## Page structure

Product and content pages follow a consistent pattern:
1. `PageHero` with eyebrow, title, optional subtitle
2. `Section` blocks for content groups
3. `GlassPanel` for card surfaces
4. `CardHeader` / `CardFooter` for panel chrome

Lab dashboard pages use a flat `div` layout with `space-y-8` instead of `Section` wrappers
to avoid excessive vertical padding.

## Component patterns

- No prop drilling beyond 2 levels. Use component composition.
- Click-outside-to-close: every dropdown and expandable panel must use `useRef` + `useEffect`
  with a `mousedown` listener on `document`.
- Escape key: dropdowns should also close on Escape via a `keydown` listener.
- Only one expandable panel open at a time per component group.

## Accessibility

- Interactive elements need `aria-label` or visible text.
- Decorative elements need `aria-hidden="true"`.
- SVG icons that convey meaning need `role="img"` and a title.
- The nav has a skip-to-content link — preserve it.

## Metadata

- Every page exports metadata via `pageMetadata()` from `lib/metadata.ts`.
- Product pages export `export const metadata = pageMetadata(title, description, path)`.
- Dynamic pages use `generateMetadata` with awaited params.
